                  <handDesc>
                     <handNote>The hand of MS 151 (an elegant Continental bookhand similar to that of MS 150 but angled forward).</handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  <decoDesc>
                     <decoNote>As for MS 150 (large initials, typical English professional work of the period): fols. <locus>3</locus> (Ps. 52), <locus>59v</locus> (Ps. 68), <locus>124</locus> (Ps. 80), <locus>185</locus> (Ps. 96), <locus>239</locus> (Ps. 109) 5–7-line initials with 3-sided borders; on fols. <locus>1</locus>, <locus>192v</locus> (Ps. 101) 8–9-line blue initials on a square ground of red flourishing; blue initials flourished in red; red marginal <hi rend="italic">auctoritates</hi>, highlighting, and underlining of scriptural passages, running heads on or between ruled lines.</decoNote>
                  </decoDesc>
                  <bindingDesc>
                     <binding calendar="Gregorian" notAfter="1700" notBefore="1600">
                        <p>Standard Merton s. xvii; sewn on five bands; formerly chained from the usual position. Fols. i-ii, 310–11 are paper binding-leaves, the outermost from the same printed book as in MS 19.</p>
                     </binding>
